<highlight>
<T1>the arraignment for khalid sheikh mohammed and four other 9/11 defendants lasted 13 hours due to their defiance and refusal to cooperate.</T1>

<T1.1>the five men appeared together in a military courtroom for the first time since 2008.</T1.1>
<T1.1.1>they were charged last month for their alleged role in planning and executing the september 11, 2001 terror attacks.</T1.1.1>
<T1.1.2>nearly 3,000 people were killed in the attacks.</T1.1.2>

<T1.2>the defendants deliberately disrupted the proceedings and refused to follow courtroom protocol.</T1.2>
<T1.2.1>they ignored the judge's instructions and refused to speak or cooperate.</T1.2.1>
<T1.2.2>mohammed's lawyer stated his client would "decline to communicate with the court."</T1.2.2>
<T1.2.3>the silence and refusal to speak slowed the proceedings and caused issues with court translations.</T1.2.3>

<T1.3>several defendants engaged in specific acts of defiance during the hearing.</T1.3>
<T1.3.1>bin 'attash was initially wheeled into court in a restraining chair.</T1.3.1>
<T1.3.1.1>he later took off his shirt while his attorney described injuries he allegedly sustained in custody.</T1.3.1.1>
<T1.3.1.2>he made a paper airplane and placed it on a microphone.</T1.3.1.2>
<T1.3.2>binalshibh shouted an outburst in english: "you may not see us anymore. they are going to kill us."</T1.3.2>
<T1.3.3>binalshibh led the group twice in prayer in the courtroom, delaying the resumption of the hearing.</T1.3.3>

<T1.4>despite their defiance, the judge ruled they would continue to be represented by their current attorneys.</T1.4>
<T1.4.1>the judge needed the defendants to vocally confirm their desire for representation, but they refused.</T1.4.1>
<T1.4.2>the five men chose to defer entering a plea, which is routine practice in military court.</T1.4.2>
<T1.4.3>the judge said he would enter a not guilty plea on mohammed's behalf if he refused.</T1.4.3>

<T1.5>all five men face serious charges and the possibility of the death penalty.</T1.5>
<T1.5.1>they are charged with terrorism, hijacking aircraft, conspiracy, and murder in violation of the law of war.</T1.5.1>
<T1.5.2>additional charges include attacking civilians, destroying property, and intentionally causing serious bodily injury.</T1.5.2>
<T1.5.3>if convicted, they face the death penalty.</T1.5.3>

<T1.6>the case has a long and complex legal history.</T1.6>
<T1.6.1>mohammed was initially charged in 2008, but president obama stopped the case to pursue closing guantanamo bay.</T1.6.1>
<T1.6.2>an attempt to move the case to federal court in new york in 2009 was dropped due to political opposition.</T1.6.2>
<T1.6.3>in april 2012, attorney general eric holder announced the five would face a military trial at guantanamo bay.</T1.6.3>
<T1.6.4>the next hearing is scheduled for june 12, and trial is likely at least a year away.</T1.6.4>
